WEBVTT

00:05.272 --> 00:08.407
-[soft music]
-[birds chirping]

00:22.123 --> 00:23.655
[baby babbles]

00:26.260 --> 00:27.526
Oh.

00:37.538 --> 00:39.471
[chuckles]

00:40.307 --> 00:41.607
Hi, Patrick.

00:44.478 --> 00:46.278
[sighs] Here you go.

00:48.416 --> 00:49.548
There you go.

00:51.118 --> 00:52.217
Oh.

00:53.554 --> 00:54.720
You're going to do great things.

00:55.322 --> 00:56.722
You're going to do great things.

00:58.726 --> 01:00.592
Ha. Yes, you are.

01:02.430 --> 01:04.129
[Santa] Ho, ho, ho.

01:04.131 --> 01:05.597
[chuckles]

01:05.599 --> 01:07.199
This is the one.

01:08.069 --> 01:08.801
Yes.

01:10.104 --> 01:11.603
Yes, you are.

01:11.672 --> 01:13.639
[festive music]

02:20.241 --> 02:23.308
[suspenseful music]

02:27.248 --> 02:28.814
[Joe] Tell me now, Patrick.

02:28.816 --> 02:30.282
How long have you been here?

02:30.818 --> 02:32.518
So I came over here
about a year ago.

02:32.520 --> 02:34.653
I worked on one of those
posh cruise liners.

02:34.655 --> 02:36.588
We did the Transatlantic for
about two and a half years

02:36.590 --> 02:38.490
between here and England.

02:38.492 --> 02:42.361
Um, I worked in the kitchen,
but to be honest,

02:42.429 --> 02:43.695
I kind of got tired
of the sailing life.

02:43.697 --> 02:46.598
So I got off and lost
in The Big Apple.

02:46.600 --> 02:48.734
-[chuckles]
-I got a job at
a Mexican restaurant,

02:48.736 --> 02:51.537
bar backed at
a couple of nightclubs,
paid under the table.

02:51.539 --> 02:52.504
It was quite nice.

02:53.274 --> 02:55.274
So, you have no papers then?

02:56.443 --> 02:58.644
Uh, no, uh, I don't, no.

02:59.613 --> 03:01.680
-Where are you from?
-From Derry.

03:01.749 --> 03:03.182
-Derry?
-Mm-hmm.

03:03.184 --> 03:04.483
Oh, family?

03:05.619 --> 03:07.352
I don't have a family, no.

03:07.354 --> 03:09.621
I was raised in an orphanage.

03:09.623 --> 03:11.356
Left when I was 18.

03:14.395 --> 03:16.195
Fred, where's my juice?!

03:16.197 --> 03:17.563
[woman] I got it, Fred.

03:19.366 --> 03:20.666
[sighs]

03:20.668 --> 03:21.800
[woman] Here you are.

03:23.604 --> 03:25.704
I'll be honest
with you now, Pat.

03:25.705 --> 03:27.805
I've not heard a sadder story
than that in many a year.

03:29.543 --> 03:34.780
Well... we look after
our own, hmm?

03:36.717 --> 03:39.251
I could use someone
to wash the glasses

03:39.253 --> 03:40.986
and maybe tidy up around here.

03:40.988 --> 03:42.721
Could you handle that?

03:42.723 --> 03:44.523
Absolutely, sir.

03:44.525 --> 03:46.558
I'd really appreciate
that, Mr. O'Brian.

03:46.560 --> 03:48.794
[chuckles] You can call me Joe.

03:49.797 --> 03:51.930
-Thank you, Joe.
-[Joe chuckling]
Can you start now?

03:51.932 --> 03:53.398
-Yes, right away, yeah.
-Right.

03:53.400 --> 03:54.566
-It's a pleasure.
-Get started, get started.

03:54.568 --> 03:55.934
Absolutely, thank you so much.

03:55.936 --> 03:58.470
Fred, come and show
young Patrick here the ropes.

03:58.472 --> 04:00.005
[Irish themed jolly music]

04:04.712 --> 04:05.744
Yeah.

04:05.746 --> 04:07.646
[guests laughing]

04:23.764 --> 04:25.330
Fred!

04:25.331 --> 04:26.897
you will do exactly
what I tell you to

04:26.900 --> 04:28.400
or you will have a problem.

04:28.402 --> 04:30.902
Now I do not have problems,
do you understand?

04:30.904 --> 04:32.371
I have solutions.

04:32.373 --> 04:34.906
Now get out of here
and do what I tell you!

04:44.018 --> 04:45.584
-You all right?
-Yeah, thanks.

04:52.493 --> 04:53.925
-7.50.
-Keep the change.

04:53.927 --> 04:54.860
Thanks.

04:56.497 --> 04:58.697
And I have to tell you, boys,
we had a very good month.

04:59.566 --> 05:00.899
Another month or two like this,

05:00.901 --> 05:03.735
and we're going to treat
ourselves to a little raise.

05:03.737 --> 05:05.737
[laughs]

05:06.573 --> 05:08.740
-Where are you going now?
-Well, I was thinking
maybe we'd take care

05:08.742 --> 05:10.442
of that little situation
over in Brooklyn first.

05:12.946 --> 05:14.046
Well, off you go, boys.

05:15.382 --> 05:16.848
-Enjoy your work.
-Thank you, boss.

05:16.850 --> 05:19.051
-[laughs]
-[light music]

05:21.989 --> 05:23.922
Does that remind you
of your family, Pat?

05:25.626 --> 05:28.760
You know, I've never
met my family.

05:30.364 --> 05:32.898
We didn't have Christmas
in the orphanage.
It was a poor parish.

05:32.900 --> 05:34.333
[woman] I didn't know.

05:34.335 --> 05:35.934
-That's rough.
-Yeah.

05:36.770 --> 05:38.670
Kind of miss home, you know?

05:38.672 --> 05:41.506
Of course you do.
Of course you do.

05:49.616 --> 05:56.655
<i> ¶ Oh, Danny boy, the pipes</i>
<i> The pipes are calling ¶</i>

05:57.758 --> 06:01.460
<i> ¶ From glen to glen ¶</i>

06:01.462 --> 06:05.430
<i> ¶ And down the mountain side ¶</i>

06:06.467 --> 06:09.735
<i> ¶ The summer's gone ¶</i>

06:09.737 --> 06:14.706
<i> ¶ And all the roses falling ¶</i>

06:15.542 --> 06:19.711
<i> ¶ 'Tis you, 'tis you must go ¶</i>

06:19.713 --> 06:23.782
<i> ¶ And I must bide ¶</i>

06:23.784 --> 06:28.920
<i> ¶ But come ye back</i>
<i> When summer's ¶</i>

06:28.922 --> 06:32.491
<i> ¶ In the meadow ¶</i>

06:32.493 --> 06:36.094
<i> ¶ Or when the valley's ¶</i>

06:36.096 --> 06:40.565
<i> ¶ Hushed and white With snow ¶</i>

06:41.034 --> 06:44.903
<i> ¶ 'Tis I'll be here ¶</i>

06:44.905 --> 06:50.776
<i> ¶ in sunshine or in shadow ¶</i>

06:50.778 --> 06:57.749
<i> ¶ And I will sleep in peace ¶</i>

06:58.819 --> 07:04.890
<i> ¶ Until you come ¶</i>

07:05.926 --> 07:12.464
<i> ¶ To me ¶</i>

07:17.571 --> 07:19.971
[applauding]

07:21.208 --> 07:22.607
Clap!

07:22.609 --> 07:24.576
[everyone applauding]

07:26.447 --> 07:27.746
Thank you.

07:27.748 --> 07:29.481
[whistles]

07:37.024 --> 07:40.692
Patrick, could I have
a little word with you?

07:40.694 --> 07:41.793
Yeah, sure.

07:41.795 --> 07:43.061
Be right there.

07:45.566 --> 07:46.965
Right, right, right, right.

07:49.002 --> 07:50.602
[sighs]

07:50.604 --> 07:52.137
Pat, will you do a favor for me?

07:52.806 --> 07:55.006
Yeah, whatever you need, Joe.

07:55.008 --> 07:57.676
You've been like a father figure
these past few months, Joe.

07:57.678 --> 08:00.011
Saint Joe,
Patron Saint of Fathers.

08:00.013 --> 08:02.614
-Oh. [laughs]
-That's you, Joe.

08:02.616 --> 08:04.816
I wouldn't go that far,
I'm no Saint.

08:04.885 --> 08:07.686
No, seriously, Joe, I don't
know where I would be

08:07.688 --> 08:08.887
these past few months
without your work.

08:08.889 --> 08:10.188
So, thank you.

08:11.492 --> 08:13.024
Okay, good.

08:14.962 --> 08:16.628
[light dramatic music]

08:16.630 --> 08:20.765
I want you to take these
suitcases a couple of blocks up

08:20.767 --> 08:23.602
the road to the train station
and give them to Shaun.

08:23.604 --> 08:26.638
But no opening the suitcases,

08:26.640 --> 08:29.107
no peeping inside,
you understand?

08:29.109 --> 08:30.642
Can you do that for me?

08:30.711 --> 08:33.178
[laughs] As soon as
you've done that,

08:33.179 --> 08:35.647
I'm going to
give you 10,000 clams.

08:36.984 --> 08:40.519
That's, uh, that's a lot of
money for a few blocks, Joe.

08:40.520 --> 08:42.520
It is, it is indeed.

08:42.956 --> 08:44.656
[laughs]

08:44.658 --> 08:46.258
Let me explain,
let me explain to you.

08:47.594 --> 08:50.662
Do you know what the hardest
thing in business is, son?

08:51.932 --> 08:54.933
The hardest thing
in business, Pat,

08:56.136 --> 09:00.739
is to find people that you
can trust and I trust you.

09:04.745 --> 09:05.878
I trust you.

09:05.879 --> 09:07.012
Now, trust is
a valuable commodity,

09:07.014 --> 09:09.915
a commodity that
I am prepared to pay for.

09:13.053 --> 09:15.787
Well, uh, when do you
want me to leave?

09:15.789 --> 09:18.089
Now, tonight, this very moment.

09:18.091 --> 09:19.090
Shaun's waiting for you.

09:19.092 --> 09:20.325
But what about, where's Fred?

09:20.327 --> 09:21.593
Who's going to close the bar?

09:21.595 --> 09:22.294
I'll close the bar.

09:22.296 --> 09:23.962
Where is Fred?

09:23.964 --> 09:25.630
Fred?

09:25.632 --> 09:27.699
Don't you worry
yourself about Fred.

09:27.768 --> 09:29.267
Fred was untrustworthy.

09:29.269 --> 09:32.904
So, Fred, I had to let him go.

09:34.308 --> 09:36.107
Come on, quick, quick, quick.

09:38.045 --> 09:39.811
Ah, very good, very good.

09:39.813 --> 09:42.647
Oh, and now, a couple of
things, couple of things.

09:42.649 --> 09:45.617
First of all, you do not dote,

09:45.619 --> 09:48.253
you do not stop
and talk to anyone.

09:48.322 --> 09:52.257
And in the incredibly
remote chance

09:52.259 --> 09:55.894
that something goes wrong,
you take those bags

09:55.896 --> 09:58.730
and you run like hell
to the station, you understand?

09:58.732 --> 10:00.732
You run like hell.

10:00.801 --> 10:02.701
Off you go, quick.

10:02.703 --> 10:05.270
Sooner there,
sooner back, sooner paid.

10:05.272 --> 10:06.738
Oh, and put your jacket on.

10:06.740 --> 10:08.073
It's cold outside.

10:11.111 --> 10:12.677
[sirens wailing]

10:12.679 --> 10:14.179
[dogs barking]

10:14.181 --> 10:15.747
It's just a few blocks.

10:16.683 --> 10:17.916
[sighs]

10:17.918 --> 10:19.651
No big deal, right?

10:24.224 --> 10:25.557
It's just a few blocks.

10:25.558 --> 10:26.891
-Let's go, Pat.
It's just a few blocks.
-[Joe laughing]

10:26.893 --> 10:28.860
And don't worry if
the cops grab him,

10:28.862 --> 10:32.163
he's so pathetically grateful
to me for looking after him,

10:32.232 --> 10:33.865
that he'll go to
prison for 20 years

10:33.867 --> 10:35.934
-without opening his mouth.
-[muffled talking]

10:35.936 --> 10:37.902
There's a perfectly
reasonable explanation

10:37.904 --> 10:40.105
as to why I shouldn't
look inside.

10:40.107 --> 10:41.139
It's obviously
something important,

10:41.141 --> 10:42.807
like insurance policies or...

10:44.845 --> 10:46.077
a secret recipe for craft beer.

10:47.247 --> 10:49.414
[dramatic music]

10:53.420 --> 10:54.953
Deed to the pub.

10:56.323 --> 10:58.423
-[gasping]
-[suspenseful music]

11:14.808 --> 11:17.776
-[Joe laughing]
-Yeah, and the lovely
thing is this,

11:17.844 --> 11:20.412
if we do have to off him,
guess what?

11:20.414 --> 11:22.047
He has no relatives.

11:22.049 --> 11:24.749
So nobody is going to
come and look for him.

11:24.751 --> 11:26.818
And here's
the icing on the cake.

11:26.820 --> 11:28.053
He's also illegal.

11:28.121 --> 11:30.789
There is no paper
trail to suggest

11:30.791 --> 11:32.090
he ever came into the country.

11:32.159 --> 11:33.725
-When you think about it,
-[guy] Hey, watch it!

11:33.727 --> 11:35.960
The boy is practically
a ghost already.

11:35.962 --> 11:37.796
[chuckling]

11:38.398 --> 11:40.198
What's the next bus
leaving right now?

11:40.200 --> 11:41.800
[change rattling]

11:44.871 --> 11:49.140
Bus 46 is pulling out,
heading out west.

11:49.209 --> 11:50.742
[Patrick] Yeah, that's fine.
Ticket, please.

11:50.811 --> 11:52.210
[dramatic music]

12:09.730 --> 12:12.197
[Irish themed upbeat music]

12:50.270 --> 12:53.037
[bus driver] Last stop,
Santa Fe, everybody off.

12:59.379 --> 13:00.545
Please check around
your own seats.

13:00.547 --> 13:03.114
Don't leave any
belongings behind.

13:14.828 --> 13:17.362
[upbeat music]

13:31.578 --> 13:33.478
[crowd whistling]

13:44.457 --> 13:46.858
[man hollering]

13:54.034 --> 13:55.900
[muffled talking]

14:08.381 --> 14:09.914
[door creaking]

14:09.916 --> 14:12.083
[Spanish themed
acoustic guitar music]

14:33.173 --> 14:34.172
Hello?

14:37.143 --> 14:40.111
[fire crackling]

14:45.018 --> 14:46.584
Welcome to Ortegas.

14:47.153 --> 14:48.653
I'm Mrs. Ortega.

14:48.655 --> 14:50.255
Need a room?

14:50.257 --> 14:54.359
Yeah, well, um,
that depends, Mrs. Ortega.

14:54.361 --> 14:56.127
How much?

14:56.129 --> 14:59.964
Well, I'm having
a special for 49.99

14:59.966 --> 15:02.300
and that is breakfast included.

15:03.670 --> 15:05.169
I'll show you, follow me.

15:08.508 --> 15:09.607
You like?

15:09.609 --> 15:10.675
Uh, yes.

15:12.145 --> 15:13.344
Uh, very much.

15:15.181 --> 15:17.382
Can I have it for one night?

15:17.384 --> 15:19.083
[sighs] Only one night?

15:20.954 --> 15:22.921
Of course, why not.

15:22.923 --> 15:24.022
Yeah, my name is Pat by the way.

15:24.024 --> 15:26.141
Pat Keeley.

15:26.142 --> 15:28.259
Oh, please join me
for lunch,<i> Señor</i> Keeley.

15:28.261 --> 15:29.394
I made too much.

15:29.396 --> 15:31.195
I'm used to cooking for two.

15:31.197 --> 15:32.997
-So please?
-Oh.

15:32.999 --> 15:34.599
-You look hungry.
-I'm starving,

15:34.601 --> 15:36.200
-I just.
-[laughs]

15:38.605 --> 15:40.038
Thanks very much, Mrs. O.

15:40.040 --> 15:41.306
-Oh.
-It's very kind of you.

15:43.043 --> 15:45.009
I hate to eat alone.

15:45.011 --> 15:48.713
Ever since my husband died,
if I don't have company

15:48.715 --> 15:51.382
to eat with, I just don't eat.

15:52.519 --> 15:55.186
You saved me from self-imposed
starvation, you see?

15:56.456 --> 15:58.690
-[Mexican themed upbeat music]
-[coughing]

16:01.728 --> 16:03.127
The chili.

16:03.129 --> 16:04.963
Oh, I should have known.

16:04.965 --> 16:06.664
Oh, the chili.

16:08.335 --> 16:09.968
Oh, ah.

16:11.671 --> 16:13.972
[coughing]

16:13.974 --> 16:15.306
-What is that?
-Tequila.

16:15.375 --> 16:17.408
Margarita, don't you like it?

16:17.410 --> 16:19.310
-I wasn't expecting that.
-Well, okay.

16:19.312 --> 16:23.448
Have some <i> sopapilla</i> with honey
and that will cut the heat.

16:26.987 --> 16:28.619
[sighs]

16:28.621 --> 16:30.088
Thanks, Mrs. O.

16:30.557 --> 16:32.256
-There.
-[sighs]

16:32.258 --> 16:35.126
Now see, that's better.

16:38.031 --> 16:39.497
[sighs]

16:40.266 --> 16:41.532
Are you here on holidays?

16:42.235 --> 16:45.536
No. Yes... maybe?

16:48.208 --> 16:51.275
Well, I think I, I think I'm
going to go lie down for a nap.

16:51.277 --> 16:54.012
It's been a long, long journey.

16:55.782 --> 16:57.749
[groaning]

16:59.452 --> 17:00.385
God.

17:02.689 --> 17:04.789
I'm pretty sure the woman
just tried to poison me.

17:04.790 --> 17:06.491
[gentle acoustic guitar music]

17:06.492 --> 17:08.459
-[dogs howling]
-[owls hooting]

17:24.544 --> 17:26.544
[owl hooting]

17:31.618 --> 17:33.351
[groaning]

17:49.636 --> 17:52.203
-[dog barking]
-[coins clanking]

17:52.205 --> 17:54.806
[phone beeping]

17:57.444 --> 17:59.444
-[phone ringing]
-[Joe] <i> Yes?</i>

17:59.512 --> 18:01.179
<i> -Joe?</i>
-Pat!

18:01.181 --> 18:02.780
[dramatic music]

18:02.782 --> 18:04.782
Where the hell are you?

18:04.784 --> 18:06.384
<i> Where the devil are you?!</i>

18:06.386 --> 18:08.853
Ah, Joe, so, um, I started
doing what you asked

18:08.855 --> 18:11.155
in delivering
the cases, but, um,

18:11.157 --> 18:12.824
but these guys started
following me, Joe,

18:12.826 --> 18:14.792
and then the police were
coming straight at me.

18:14.794 --> 18:16.794
<i> So, I had to take</i>
<i> a quick detour.</i>

18:16.796 --> 18:19.097
Do you still have the
suitcases with you?!

18:19.165 --> 18:20.798
I do, I, I, I have the cases.

18:20.800 --> 18:22.467
Um, and I haven't looked
in them like you said.

18:22.469 --> 18:26.404
No, you listen to me,
get those suitcases back here.

18:26.473 --> 18:28.873
<i> I will bury you</i>
<i> with my own bare hands!</i>

18:29.142 --> 18:31.542
Where the hell are ya?!

18:31.544 --> 18:36.114
Joe, I'm in New-- I'm going to
have to call you back, Joe.

18:38.318 --> 18:40.284
[light dramatic music]

18:46.159 --> 18:47.625
Okay,

18:48.695 --> 18:50.528
505.

18:56.136 --> 18:58.169
[light suspenseful music]

19:22.295 --> 19:23.227
[clears throat]

19:26.432 --> 19:28.432
Fred is no longer with us.

19:28.434 --> 19:30.501
Fred was untrustworthy.

19:30.503 --> 19:32.170
Lord....

19:33.239 --> 19:34.872
please don't let that
be Freddie in there.

19:37.577 --> 19:40.678
[suspenseful music]

19:43.850 --> 19:45.783
-[uplifting music]
-That's not Fred!

19:49.289 --> 19:50.454
That's not Fred!

19:51.591 --> 19:53.624
Oh, sweet Lord on high.

19:53.626 --> 19:54.625
Thank you for
making the contents

19:54.627 --> 19:57.228
of these here cases not Fred.

19:59.399 --> 20:01.933
[Irish themed upbeat music]

20:14.781 --> 20:16.480
[sighs]

20:18.685 --> 20:19.750
One million.

20:21.721 --> 20:22.653
300,000.

20:25.358 --> 20:26.290
And two dollars.

20:26.926 --> 20:27.858
Two dollars.

20:29.562 --> 20:31.662
[laughs] Oh, my.

20:32.765 --> 20:34.899
Mrs. Ortega, Mrs. Ortega.

20:35.835 --> 20:37.702
Make me some mashed
potatoes and steak, yeah?

20:37.770 --> 20:40.304
And some of those little
pastry pillows with the honey?

20:40.306 --> 20:41.372
But we don't have no steak.

20:41.374 --> 20:42.873
We only have lamb chops.

20:42.875 --> 20:44.275
-Wonderful.
-[chuckles]

20:44.277 --> 20:45.876
-Lamb chops for two.
-Mm-hmm.

20:45.878 --> 20:48.012
Won't you join me,
<i> Señora</i> Ortega?

20:48.014 --> 20:49.313
-Ooh.
-It's on me.

20:49.315 --> 20:50.581
-[gasping]
-And now, missus,

20:50.583 --> 20:51.983
let's forget
about the tequila, yeah?

20:51.985 --> 20:53.951
-Oh.
-Your finest bottle
of champagne.

20:53.953 --> 20:56.487
-Actually, make it two,<i> Señora.</i>
-Oh.

20:56.489 --> 20:58.456
-And then,<i> Señora.</i>
-Uh huh?

20:58.458 --> 20:59.890
I think I'm going to be
staying here for a while.

20:59.892 --> 21:02.293
-Hmm.
-I like it here very much.

21:02.295 --> 21:04.495
-I like that, too.
-Very much indeed.

21:04.497 --> 21:06.664
Hmm, a little nap did a whole

21:06.666 --> 21:09.033
wide world of good,
<i> Señor</i> Keeley.

21:09.035 --> 21:12.270
[chuckling]
Mrs., I'll tell you what,
just goes to show you,

21:12.272 --> 21:14.472
when the world seems at an end,

21:14.474 --> 21:16.340
shut your eyes, open them again.

21:16.342 --> 21:17.441
-[snaps fingers]
-Hmm.

